## 1. Core Philosophy

This project uses an Atomic CSS (also known as Functional CSS) approach for styling. The goal is to use a collection of small, single-purpose, immutable utility classes directly in the HTML to compose user interfaces. This approach is favored to improve clarity, reduce CSS file size, and avoid complex specificity wars or the need for `!important` overrides.

## 2. Behavioral Directives

-   **MUST** prefer using existing utility classes over writing new, component-specific CSS.
-   **MUST NOT** create large, monolithic CSS classes that style an entire component (e.g., `.profile-card { ... }`). Instead, compose the component's style from smaller utilities (e.g., `<div class="p-4 rounded-lg shadow-md">`).
-   **SHOULD** generate new utility classes using the project's tooling if a required utility does not exist, rather than adding one-off styles.
-   **MUST NOT** use element selectors (e.g., `div`, `p`, `h1`) for styling. All styles should be applied via classes.
-   **AVOID** deep nesting in CSS. The methodology should result in a flat CSS file structure.

## 3. Practical Examples

### ❌ Bad: Component-Based CSS

**HTML:**

```html
<div class="profile-card">
  <h3>User Name</h3>
  <p>User description...</p>
</div>
```

**CSS:**

```css
.profile-card {
  padding: 1rem;
  border-radius: 0.5rem;
  box-shadow: 0 4px 6px -1px rgb(0 0 0 / 0.1), 0 2px 4px -2px rgb(0 0 0 / 0.1);
  background-color: #fff;
}
```

**Why it's bad:** This creates a new, non-reusable class that adds to the CSS file size and can lead to specificity conflicts later.

### ✅ Good: Atomic CSS Composition

**HTML:**

```html
<div class="p-4 rounded-lg shadow-md bg-white">
  <h3 class="text-xl font-bold mb-2">User Name</h3>
  <p class="text-gray-700">User description...</p>
</div>
```

**CSS (assumes these utility classes exist):**

```css
.p-4 { padding: 1rem; }
.rounded-lg { border-radius: 0.5rem; }
.shadow-md { box-shadow: 0 4px 6px -1px rgb(0 0 0 / 0.1), 0 2px 4px -2px rgb(0 0 0 / 0.1); }
.bg-white { background-color: #fff; }
/* ... and so on for text, font, margin, etc. */
```

**Why it's good:** Each class is a reusable utility. The styling is immediately clear from reading the HTML, and no new CSS needs to be written for this component.

## 4. Rationale

Atomic CSS ensures maintainability, clarity, and scalability by enforcing a "one class, one property" approach. This reduces specificity conflicts, eliminates the need for `!important`, and makes it easy to reason about and reuse styles. It also keeps CSS files smaller and more efficient.

## 5. Checklist for Atomic CSS

-   [ ] Is each class atomic (one property, one value)?
-   [ ] Are all layout and spacing handled by utility classes?
-   [ ] Are there any `!important` overrides? (If yes, refactor)
-   [ ] Are there any element selectors or deep nesting? (If yes, refactor)
-   [ ] Is all CSS consolidated into a single file?

## 6. Explicit Rules

-   **One class, one property:** Each atomic class must represent a single CSS property-value pair (e.g., `.p-4 { padding: 1rem; }`).
-   **No `!important`:** Do not use `!important` in atomic classes.
-   **No element selectors or deep nesting:** All styles must be applied via classes only, and CSS should be flat.

## 7. Reference: atomic-utilities.css

All atomic utility classes are defined in [`atomic-utilities.css`](../../atomic-css/atomic-utilities.css). When you need a new utility, add it there following the atomic pattern.

## 8. More Real Examples

**Good (from atomic-utilities.css):**

```css
.p-4 { padding: 1rem; }
.text-center { text-align: center; }
.font-bold { font-weight: bold; }
.rounded { border-radius: 0.25rem; }
```

**Bad:**

```css
.card { margin: 1rem 0 2rem 0; padding: 2rem; background: #fff; }
div > p { color: red !important; }


.rounded-lg { border-radius: 0.5rem; }
.shadow-md { box-shadow: 0 4px 6px -1px rgb(0 0 0 / 0.1), 0 2px 4px -2px rgb(0 0 0 / 0.1); }
.bg-white { background-color: #fff; }
/*... and so on for text, font, margin, etc.*/

```

**Why it's good:** Each class is a reusable utility. The styling is immediately clear from reading the HTML, and no new CSS needs to be written for this component.
